# BUSOS Vertical Engine — Architecture & Configuration

The BUSOS platform supports multiple industry verticals from a single codebase. All vertical-specific behaviour is driven by configuration, not separate codebases.

## Core Architecture

| Component | File | Purpose |
|---|---|---|
| `Vertical` enum | `apps/web/prisma/schema.prisma` | Flags which industry a venture belongs to |
| `Venture.vertical` field | `apps/web/prisma/schema.prisma` | Stores the vertical for each venture |
| `VerticalConfig` library | `apps/web/lib/vertical-config.ts` | Central source of truth for all vertical configs |
| Milestone generation | `apps/web/app/api/ventures/[ventureId]/milestones/generate/route.ts` | Reads the vertical config to extend Ada's system prompt |

## Adding a New Vertical

Follow these steps in order:

### Step 1: Schema

Add the new vertical ID to the `Vertical` enum in `schema.prisma`:

```prisma
enum Vertical {
  GENERAL
  BIOTECH
  PROPERTY_DEV
  FINTECH  // <- add new vertical here
}
```

Add any vertical-specific fields to `VentureDNA` in `schema.prisma` (all optional):

```prisma
model VentureDNA {
  // ... existing fields
  // FINTECH fields
  regulatoryBody   String? @db.Text
  licenceRequired  String? @db.Text
}
```

Run `npx prisma generate` after schema changes.

### Step 2: VerticalConfig Library

Add a new entry to `VERTICAL_CONFIGS` in `apps/web/lib/vertical-config.ts`. Every config must include:

```typescript
[Vertical.FINTECH]: {
  id: Vertical.FINTECH,
  displayName: "FinTech / Financial Services",
  dnaFields: [
    { name: "regulatoryBody", label: "Primary Regulator", placeholder: "e.g., FCA, SEC, FINRA" },
    { name: "licenceRequired", label: "Licence Required", placeholder: "e.g., EMI Licence, Broker-Dealer" },
  ],
  adaPromptExtension: `This is a **fintech** venture. [Domain-specific Ada guidance here...]`,
  milestoneCategories: ["VALIDATION", "REGULATORY_LICENCE", "BANKING_PARTNER", "PRODUCT", "COMPLIANCE", "GROWTH"],
},
```

### Step 3: Milestone Generation

The `milestones/generate/route.ts` already reads `venture.vertical` and calls `getSystemPrompt(vertical)`. No changes are needed to this file when adding a new vertical — the config library handles it automatically.

### Step 4: Onboarding

The vertical selector in `apps/web/app/(app)/dream/page.tsx` is populated from `VERTICAL_CONFIGS`. No changes are needed here either — the new vertical will appear automatically once added to the config library.

## Existing Verticals

### GENERAL
The default. Generic startup journey covering Validation, Legal, Financial, Product, Growth, IP, and Operations.

### BIOTECH
Science-driven journey for life sciences founders. Key stages: Discovery → Pre-Clinical → IND/Regulatory → Clinical Phase I → Series A → Phase II/III → Exit. Ada is prompted to focus on IP, regulatory pathways (FDA/EMA), non-dilutive funding (SBIR/STTR), and M&A exit strategy.

### PROPERTY_DEV
Project-driven journey for residential property developers. Key stages: Deal Analysis → Due Diligence → Acquisition Financing → Planning Approvals → Construction → Marketing/Sales → Exit. Ada is prompted to focus on feasibility, planning permission, construction loans, and defined exit (for-sale vs build-to-rent).

## Non-Negotiable Rules

- Every vertical must have an `adaPromptExtension` that is specific, domain-aware, and at least 3 bullet points long.
- Every vertical must define `milestoneCategories` — Ada uses these as the allowed category values when generating the journey.
- Never hardcode vertical-specific logic outside of `vertical-config.ts`. All branching must be driven by the config object.
